  "prompt": "Why is big G used in the formula of force?",
  "response": "Big G, known as the gravitational constant, is used in the formula for calculating the gravitational force between two masses. It represents the strength of the gravitational force and is a key part of Newton's law of universal gravitation.\n\nThe formula for the gravitational force is:\n\n\\[ F = \\frac{G \\cdot m_1 \\cdot m_2}{r^2}, \\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( F \\) is the gravitational force between the two masses,\n- \\( G \\) is the gravitational constant,\n- \\( m_1 \\) and \\( m_2 \\) are the masses of the two objects, and\n- \\( r \\) is the distance between the centers of the two masses.\n\nBig G is a fundamental constant in physics with an approximate value of \\( 6.67430 \\times 10^{-11} \\, \\text{m}^3 \\text{kg}^{-1} \\text{s}^{-2} \\). Its inclusion in the formula ensures that the calculated force has the correct units and magnitude, and it reflects the proportionate relationship between the masses and the distance.",
